Like a Desi tiramisu. It tasted great!! but not perfect. There‚Äôs a magical dish here that a better cook than me can finesse. :)  The story of how coffee came to India is hugely important. Baba Budan on a simple pilgramage managed to sneak just seven coffee beans out of the Yemeni blockade for his own and his people‚Äôs use, but the Yemeni blockade sought to protect the coffee market from encroaching European powers looking to profit from the trade and destabilise the region.  Somehow a Dutch governor gets his hands on Budans seeds and it one of many chain of events that have a global impact on the whole world. Coffee, like many other commodities, become the driving force that leads to an age of colonialism across Asia, Africa and the Americas.  Budan is revered as a saint in Chandragiri, for the immense benefit and leadership he brought to his people, and til today Muslim AND Hindu pilgrims pay respects to his grave, which is surrounded by gorgeous hills of coffee plants. The descendants of the original seven seeds he brought back with him.  I also used my good friend and brother @mokhtar_alkhanshali coffee from @portofmokha ! So cool using coffee that pays homage to the history of Mokha in a story that includes the actual port of Mokha! They‚Äôre the best coffee beans I‚Äôve ever had!
